explanation:
charsequalcaseless: The function is called repeatedly to decide token matching. To determine whether those calls are pure (no side effects) and thus removable without changing behaviour, the implementation of charsequalcaseless must be inspected. If it has side effects (e.g. modifies global state, errno, or performs I/O), those calls are not dead code.

isasciiupper: charsequalcaseless calls isasciiupper (per the static graph). To conclude charsequalcaseless is side-effect-free you must inspect its callees; isasciiupper (or equivalent macro/function) must be checked for side effects or non-obvious behaviour (macros can expand to locale/global-dependent code).

mhd_assert: The function uses mhd_assert around memchr calls and elsewhere. Depending on its definition (active runtime check vs. compiled-out no-op vs. longjmp/abort), those assertion calls may have observable effects. To decide if removing them would change behaviour, you must know whether mhd_assert can terminate the program or otherwise affect state.

memchr: Used inside the mhd_assert checks at the function start. Even if wrapped in an assert, memchr must be examined to confirm it has no side effects; and to understand whether those initial checks could alter behaviour if assertions are enabled/disabled.

memcpy: Used to copy token data into the output buffer. memcpy obviously has side effects (writes to buf); you must inspect its semantics (and any project-specific replacement/overrides) to determine that those copies are required for correct behaviour and therefore are not dead code.

SSIZE_MAX: The overflow/guard check uses SSIZE_MAX to decide whether to abort and set *buf_size = -1. The numeric limit and semantics of ssize_t/SSIZE_MAX affect whether that branch can be taken; to decide if that branch is ever executed or is redundant (dead) you must know the platform limits (SSIZE_MAX) and type widths.
